---
import Feature from '../../layouts/Feature.astro';
import { keys } from '../../lib/keybindings';
---

<Feature
  title="TABS"
  subtitle="Chrome-style tab management with tear-off, drag, and reordering."
>
  <h2>Chrome-Style Tabs</h2>
  <p>Tabs in ori-term work the way you expect from a browser. Tear a tab off into its own window by dragging it out, drag it back in to rejoin, and reorder tabs with smooth animation. Every operation feels instant.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><kbd>{keys.newTab}</kbd> — New tab</li>
    <li><kbd>{keys.closeTab}</kbd> — Close tab</li>
    <li><kbd>{keys.nextTab}</kbd> / <kbd>{keys.prevTab}</kbd> — Next / previous tab</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tab Width Lock</h2>
  <p>When closing tabs in rapid succession, the tab bar locks widths so close buttons stay aligned under your cursor. No more chasing a shifting close button across the bar.</p>

  <h2>Bell Animation</h2>
  <p>Inactive tabs that receive a terminal bell signal show a pulsing background animation, drawing your attention without switching focus.</p>

  <h2>Context Menus</h2>
  <p>Right-click a tab for a GPU-rendered context menu with drop shadows, hover highlighting, and separators. Actions include close, duplicate, move to new window, and more.</p>

  <h2>Settings UI</h2>
  <p>Access the settings panel with <kbd>{keys.openSettings}</kbd> to select color schemes with visual checkmark indicators. The settings UI is rendered inline using the same GPU pipeline as the rest of the chrome.</p>

  <h2>Window Controls</h2>
  <p>Minimize, maximize, and close buttons are rendered per platform — rectangular on Windows, circular on macOS. Controls are integrated into the tab bar for a clean, frameless look.</p>

  <h2>Frameless Drag</h2>
  <p>The tab bar doubles as the title bar. Drag to move the window, double-click to maximize, and drag to screen edges for Aero Snap support on Windows.</p>
</Feature>
